Key Match Events: Max O'Dowd anchored the Netherlands chase with a calm and composed half-century, carrying his bat as the Dutch reached 109/4 and won with seven balls to spare.
Netherlands bowling attack restricted Nepal to 106 all out in the first innings.
Sompal Kami had Michael Levitt caught in just the second over.
O'Dowd and Vikramjit Singh settled any Dutch nerves with a steady 40-run partnership.
Sybrand Engelbrecht added a helpful 14 from 16 to bring the target within reach.
Max O'Dowd finished unbeaten on 54* from 48 balls.
Bas de Leede hit the winning runs to end on 11*(10).
Tim Pringle removed Aasif Sheikh for 4 from 8.
Logan van Beek trapped Kushal Bhurtel lbw for 7 from 10.
Logan van Beek wrapped up the Nepalese innings with back-to-back wickets, finishing with 3/18 from 3.2 overs.
Pringle finished with 3/20 from his four overs.
Pre-Game Insights: A rain shower delayed the toss by half an hour, prompting fears of a reduced-overs contest.
Netherlands captain Scott Edwards opted to bowl first after winning the toss.
Miscellaneous Highlights: Nepal's captain Rohit Paudel was the only batter to look comfortable, scoring 35 from 37.
Lower-order runs from Gulsan Jha (14 from 15) and Karan KC (17 from 12) helped Nepal reach triple figures.
The match was played in front of a packed crowd at the Grand Prairie Cricket Stadium in Dallas.
Both teams knew that victory in this game was likely to be crucial for their chances of making it out of Group D.
